            <h1>Hypergeometric Distribution</h1>
            <p>The probability distribution of a hypergeometric random vari=
able is called a=20
        <strong>hypergeometric distribution.</strong> This lesson describes=
 how=20
        hypergeometric random variables, hypergeometric experiments,=20
        hypergeometric probability, and the hypergeometric distribution are
        all related.
    </p>
                   =20
    <h2>Notation</h2>
    <p>The following notation is helpful, when we talk about hypergeometric=
=20
	    distributions and hypergeometric probability.
    </p>
    <ul>
	    <li class=3D"extraLineSpace">
		    <i>N</i>: The number of items in the <a href=3D"https://stattrek.com/=
statistics/dictionary?definition=3DPopulation">
			    population</a>.</li>
	    <li class=3D"extraLineSpace">
		    <i>k</i>: The number of items in the population that are classified a=
s=20
	    successes.</li>
	    <li class=3D"extraLineSpace">
		    <i>n</i>: The number of items in the <a href=3D"https://stattrek.com/=
statistics/dictionary?definition=3DSample">
			    sample</a>.</li>
	    <li class=3D"extraLineSpace">
		    <i>x</i>: The number of items in the sample that are classified as=20
	    successes.</li>
	    <li class=3D"extraLineSpace">
		    <sub>k</sub>C<sub>x</sub>: The number of <a href=3D"https://stattrek.=
com/statistics/dictionary?definition=3DCombination">
			    combinations</a> of <i>k</i> things, taken <i>x</i>
	    at a time.</li>
	    <li>
		    h(<i>x</i>; <i>N</i>, <i>n</i>, <i>k</i>): <strong>hypergeometric pro=
bability</strong>
		    - the probability that an <i>n</i>-trial hypergeometric experiment re=
sults in <u>exactly</u>
		    <i>x</i> successes, when the population consists of <i>N</i> items, <=
i>k</i> of=20
		    which are classified as successes.
	    </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Hypergeometric Experiments</h2>
    <p>A <strong>hypergeometric experiment</strong> is a <a href=3D"https:/=
/stattrek.com/statistics/dictionary?definition=3DStatistical_experiment">
	    statistical experiment</a> that has the following properties:
    </p>
    <ul>
	    <li class=3D"extraLineSpace">
		    A <a href=3D"https://stattrek.com/statistics/dictionary?definition=3D=
Sample">sample</a> of size <i>n</i> is=20
		    randomly selected=20
		    <a href=3D"https://stattrek.com/statistics/dictionary?definition=3DSa=
mpling%20without%20replacement">
		    without replacement</a>
		    from a <a href=3D"https://stattrek.com/statistics/dictionary?definiti=
on=3DPopulation">
			    population</a> of <i>N</i>
	    items.</li>
	    <li>
		    In the population, <i>k</i> items can be classified as successes, and=
 <i>N - k</i>
		    items can be classified as failures.
	    </li>
    </ul>
    <p>Consider the following statistical experiment. You have an urn of 10=
 marbles - 5=20
	    red and 5 green. You randomly select 2 marbles without replacement and=
 count=20
	    the number of red marbles you have selected. This would be a hypergeom=
etric=20
	    experiment.
    </p>
    <p>Note that it would not be a <a href=3D"https://stattrek.com/statisti=
cs/dictionary?definition=3DBinomial_experiment">
		    binomial experiment</a>. A binomial experiment requires that the=20
	    probability of success be constant on every trial. With the above expe=
riment,=20
	    the probability of a success changes on every trial. In the beginning,=
 the=20
	    probability of selecting a red marble is 5/10. If you select a red mar=
ble on=20
	    the first trial, the probability of selecting a red marble on the seco=
nd trial=20
	    is 4/9. And if you select a green marble on the first trial, the proba=
bility of=20
	    selecting a red marble on the second trial is 5/9.
    </p>
    <p>Note further that if you selected the marbles with replacement, the =
probability=20
	    of success would not change. It would be 5/10 on every trial. Then, th=
is would=20
	    be a binomial experiment.
    </p>

    <div class=3D"ad_Content">


    <!-- Ezoic - incontent1 - under_first_paragraph -->
	<div id=3D"ezoic-pub-ad-placeholder-198"></div>
	<!-- End Ezoic - incontent1 - under_first_paragraph -->
</div>
    <h2>Hypergeometric Distribution</h2>
    <p>A <strong>hypergeometric random variable</strong> is the number of=
=20
	    successes that result from a hypergeometric experiment. The=20
	    <a href=3D"https://stattrek.com/statistics/dictionary?definition=3DPro=
bability_distribution">
	    probability distribution</a> of a hypergeometric random variable is ca=
lled=20
	    a <strong>hypergeometric distribution</strong>.
    </p>
    <p>Given <i>x</i>, <i>N</i>, <i>n</i>, and <i>k</i>, we can compute the=
=20
	    hypergeometric probability based on the following formula:
    </p>

    <div class=3D"CalcAd">
	    <p><strong>Hypergeometric Formula.</strong>. Suppose a=20
		population consists of <i>N</i> items, <i>k</i> of which are successes. A=
nd a=20
		random sample drawn from that population consists of <i>n</i> items, <i>x=
</i> of=20
		which are successes. Then the hypergeometric probability is:</p>

        <p style=3D"text-align:center;">h(<i>x</i>; <i>N</i>, <i>n</i>, <i>=
k</i>) =3D [ <sub>k</sub>C<sub>x</sub> ] [ <sub>N-k</sub>C<sub>n-x</sub>
			] / [ <sub>N</sub>C<sub>n</sub> ]</p>

                <p>
                    where <sub>n</sub>C<sub>r</sub> is the number of <a hre=
f=3D"https://stattrek.com/statistics/dictionary?definition=3DCombination">
                        combinations
                    </a> of <i>n</i> things, taken <i>r</i> at a time.
                </p>
    </div>



           =20
           =20

            <div class=3D"and">
                <h2>What Is a Combination?</h2>
                <p>
                    A combination represents the number of ways to choose r=
 items from a set of n items without regard to order.
                    The notation for a combination is typically written as:
                </p>
                <div style=3D"display:flex; justify-content:center; margin:=
-1rem auto;">
                    <div style=3D"font-size:.9rem; color:#555555;">
                        <mjx-container class=3D"MathJax CtxtMenu_Attached_0=
