            </div>


            <p>The hypergeometric distribution has the following properties=
:
    </p>
    <ul>
	    <li class=3D"extraLineSpace">The mean of the distribution is equal to =
n * k / N .</li>
	    <li>The <a href=3D"https://stattrek.com/statistics/dictionary?definiti=
on=3DVariance">variance</a>=20
	    is n * (k/N) * [ (N - k)/N ] * [ (N - n) / (N - 1) ].</li>
    </ul>
            <p><b>Note:</b> The variance can also be expressed in terms of =
the probability of success (p =3D k/N=E2=80=8B):</p>
            <p style=3D"text-align: center;">Variance =3D n * p * (1 - p) *=
 [ (N - n) / (N - 1) ]</p>

    <p><b>Example 1</b><br>
	    <br>
	    Suppose we randomly select 5 cards without replacement from an ordinar=
y deck of=20
	    playing cards. What is the probability of getting exactly 2 red cards =
(i.e.,=20
	    hearts or diamonds)?
    </p>
    <p><i>Solution:</i> This is a hypergeometric experiment in which we kno=
w the=20
	    following:
    </p>
    <ul>
	    <li class=3D"extraLineSpace">
	    N =3D 52; since there are 52 cards in a deck.</li>
	    <li class=3D"extraLineSpace">
	    k =3D 26; since there are 26 red cards in a deck.</li>
	    <li class=3D"extraLineSpace">
	    n =3D 5; since we randomly select 5 cards from the deck.</li>
	    <li>
		    x =3D 2; since 2 of the cards we select are red.
	    </li>
    </ul>
    <p>We plug these values into the hypergeometric formula as follows:</p>
    <p style=3D"text-align: center;">
	    h(<i>x</i>; <i>N</i>, <i>n</i>, <i>k</i>) =3D [ <sub>k</sub>C<sub>x</s=
ub> ] [ <sub>N-k</sub>C<sub>n-x</sub> ] / [ <sub>N</sub>C<sub>n</sub> ]</p>
	<p style=3D"text-align: center;">h(<i>2</i>; <i>52</i>, <i>5</i>, <i>26</i=
>) =3D [ <sub>26</sub>C<sub>2</sub> ] [ <sub>26</sub>C<sub>3</sub> ] / [ <s=
ub>52</sub>C<sub>5</sub> ]</p>
	<p style=3D"text-align: center;">h(<i>2</i>; <i>52</i>, <i>5</i>, <i>26</i=
>) =3D [ 325 ] [ 2600 ] / [ 2,598,960 ]</p>
     <p style=3D"text-align: center;">h(<i>2</i>; <i>52</i>, <i>5</i>, <i>2=
6</i>) =3D 0.32513</p>
    <p>Thus, the probability of randomly selecting 2 red cards is 0.32513.
    </p>

