	<!-- End Ezoic - incontent1 - under_first_paragraph -->
</div>
    <h2>Cumulative Hypergeometric Probability</h2>
    <p>A <strong>cumulative hypergeometric probability</strong> refers to t=
he=20
	    probability that the hypergeometric random variable is greater than or=
 equal to=20
	    some specified lower limit and less than or equal to some specified=20
	    upper limit.</p>
    <p>For example, suppose we randomly select five cards from an ordinary =
deck of=20
	    playing cards. We might be interested in the cumulative hypergeometric=
=20
	    probability of obtaining 2 or fewer hearts. This would be the probabil=
ity of=20
	    obtaining 0 hearts plus the probability of obtaining 1 heart plus the=
=20
	    probability of obtaining 2 hearts, as shown in the example below.
    </p>
    <p><b>Example 2</b><br>
	    <br>
	    Suppose we select 5 cards from an ordinary deck of playing cards. What=
 is the=20
	    probability of obtaining 2 or fewer hearts?
    </p>
    <p><i>Solution:</i> This is a hypergeometric experiment in which we kno=
w the=20
	    following:
    </p>
    <ul>
	    <li class=3D"extraLineSpace">
	    N =3D 52; since there are 52 cards in a deck.</li>
	    <li class=3D"extraLineSpace">
	    k =3D 13; since there are 13 hearts in a deck.</li>
	    <li class=3D"extraLineSpace">
	    n =3D 5; since we randomly select 5 cards from the deck.</li>
	    <li>
		    x =3D 0 to 2; since our selection includes 0, 1, or 2 hearts.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>We plug these values into the hypergeometric formula as follows:</p>
    <p style=3D"text-align: center;">
	    h(<i>x</i> <u>&lt;</u> x; <i>N</i>, <i>n</i>, <i>k</i>) =3D h(<i>x</i>=
 <u>&lt;</u>
	    2; <i>52</i>, <i>5</i>, <i>13</i>)</p>
	<p style=3D"text-align: center;">h(<i>x</i> <u>&lt;</u> 2; <i>52</i>, <i>5=
</i>, <i>13</i>) =3D h(<i>x</i> =3D 0; <i>52</i>,
	    <i>5</i>, <i>13</i>) + h(<i>x</i> =3D 1; <i>52</i>, <i>5</i>, <i>13</i=
>) + h(<i>x</i>
	    =3D 2; <i>52</i>, <i>5</i>, <i>13</i>)</p>
	<p style=3D"text-align: center;">h(<i>x</i> <u>&lt;</u> 2; <i>52</i>, <i>5=
</i>, <i>13</i>) =3D [ (<sub>13</sub>C<sub>0</sub>)=20
	    (<sub>39</sub>C<sub>5</sub>) / (<sub>52</sub>C<sub>5</sub>) ] + [ (<su=
b>13</sub>C<sub>1</sub>)=20
	    (<sub>39</sub>C<sub>4</sub>) / (<sub>52</sub>C<sub>5</sub>) ] + [ (<su=
b>13</sub>C<sub>2</sub>)=20
	    (<sub>39</sub>C<sub>3</sub>) / (<sub>52</sub>C<sub>5</sub>) ]</p>
	<p style=3D"text-align: center;">h(<i>x</i> <u>&lt;</u> 2; <i>52</i>, <i>5=
</i>, <i>13</i>) =3D [=20
	    (1)(575,757)/(2,598,960) ] + [ (13)(82,251)/(2,598,960) ] + [ (78)(913=
9)/(2,598,960) ]</p>
	<p style=3D"text-align: center;">h(<i>x</i> <u>&lt;</u> 2; <i>52</i>, <i>5=
</i>, <i>13</i>) =3D [ 0.2215 ] + [=20
	    0.4114 ] + [ 0.2743 ]</p>
	<p style=3D"text-align: center;">h(<i>x</i> <u>&lt;</u> 2; <i>52</i>, <i>5=
</i>, <i>13</i>) =3D 0.9072</p>
    <p>Thus, the probability of randomly selecting at most 2 hearts is 0.90=
72.
    </p>=20

